      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "NIH predictions compared against experimental measurements at all 5 operating points using area metric (Ferson et al. 2008). Area metric value 0.043 (threshold 0.10). Bland-Altman analysis shows no systematic bias (mean difference −0.0008 g/100 L, 95% LoA ±0.0071 g/100 L). Both NIH and pressure-head compared; agreement documented in validation report VR-2025-011.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/oc-001",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — Gradation 3",
        "description": "Quantitative comparison metric (area metric or equivalent) must be computed for primary QoI at all operating points. Area metric must be below 0.10. Bland-Altman or equivalent bias analysis must be performed. Comparison must cover at minimum the primary hemolysis QoI."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Primary QoI is NIH (g/100 L), which is the direct clinical decision metric for hemolysis acceptance per ISO 10993-4. Secondary QoIs (shear stress distribution, residence time) are mechanistically linked to NIH through the power-law hemolysis model. QoI mapping to regulatory decision documented in QoI traceability matrix QTM-2025-002.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
